data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). Use specialized collection assertions instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Shows "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows "Expected count: 3, Actual: 2" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Shows count mismatch clearly |

The `All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine with `Assert.IsTrue` since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" — but consider a descriptive message:

```csharp
Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
```

These APIs are available in MSTest 3.8+.
